{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"39e062c0-d481-4453-b138-61852cc5fb35","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` (or `.crash`) files in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Open Console.app → **Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\n2. **Core dumps** — disabled by default. Enable with:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. Core files typically appear in `/cores/`.\n\n3. **`lldb`** — attach post-mortem:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> ./YourApp\n   ```\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report includes the faulting thread, stack trace, and signal info — often enough to diagnose the issue without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1b12aa78-8f8e-4894-9b95-10f33184e1db","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":281,"requestId":"6098:7D115:2C237C:39CF2D:69FFE3D8"},"id":"46c70f18-36f3-4e88-86a4-6d823488e491","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:48:15.716Z","parentId":"50152c13-928f-4421-a27a-65ff76eeacdf"}
